Ah I see! You'd like to display an integer when your menu item is clicked? An interesting challenge indeed! This can easily be done through Tooltips in Android as they provide brief messages on interaction with UI components.

Firstly, you need to set up a Tooltip text for your item:

```xml
<item
    android:id="@+id/rssi"
    app:showAsAction="ifRoom"
    android:title=""
    android:tooltipText="YOUR_TOOLTIP_TEXT">
</item>
```
Then in java file where you handle the clicks for this specific item:

```java
@Override
public boolean onOptionsItemSelected(MenuItem item) {
    switch (item.getItemId()) {
        case R.id.rssi:
            View view = findViewById(R.id.rssi);
            String message = "Your Integer Value here!";
            int duration = Toast.LENGTH_SHORT;

            Toast toast = Toast.makeText(this, message, duration);
            toast.show();

            return true;

        default:
            return super.onOptionsItemSelected(item);
     }
}
```

This way whenever that particular icon is pressed it will cause a short message containing an integer to appear! As usual remember best practices and error handling measures - tooltips have limitations such as not being able to hold large amounts of data or be interacted with!

