Ah, a classic challenge in mobile development indeed - catering to different API levels. Fear not, there is always a workaround even when we are playing with strict rules!

For your case here where Tooltip attribute isn't supported until API 26 and you are targeting min SDK of 24, what we can do is use `PopupWindow` or `Snackbar`. Here's an example using Snackbar:

```java
@Override
public boolean onOptionsItemSelected(MenuItem item) {
    switch (item.getItemId()) {
        case R.id.rssi:
            String message = "Your Integer Value here!";
            View view = findViewById(R.id.rssi);

            Snackbar.make(view, message, Snackbar.LENGTH_LONG)
                    .setAction("Action", null).show();

            return true;

        default:
            return super.onOptionsItemSelected(item);
     }
}
```
It will accomplish essentially the same goal but accommodate older APIs.
Remember though! Snackbars also have their quirks such as not blocking user interaction with the rest of UI by design.

